07058nam a22009495i 9781487537241DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020onc    fo  d z      eng d  a2020448128  a97814875372417 a10.3138/97814875372412doi  a(DE-B1597)570898  a(OCoLC)1182930093  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON00aD810.C665bE97 2020 7aHIS0430002bisacsh00aEuropean Mennonites and the Holocaust /ced. by Mark Jantzen, John D. Thiesen. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransnational Mennonite Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction – Neighbours, Killers, Enablers, Witnesses: The Many Roles of Mennonites in the Holocaust -- tIntroduction to Chapter 1 – Mennonites and Nazi Crimes: Gerhard Rempel’s Call for Historical Reckoning -- t1 Mennonites, War Crimes, and the Holocaust -- t2 Enjoying the Entitlements of German Freedom: German Mennonites and Nazi Church-State Policy -- t3 Antisemitism and the Concept of Volk: The Mennonite Youth Circular Community at the Beginning of the Nazi Dictatorship -- t4 German Mennonite Theology in the Era of National Socialism -- t5 Dutch Mennonite Theologians and Nazism -- t6 Mennonite Collaboration with Nazism: A Case Study of the Responses of Mennonites in Deutsch Wymyschle, Poland, to the Plight of Local Jews during the Early Nazi Occupation Period (1939–1942) -- t7 Mennonites in Ukraine before, during, and Immediately after the Second World War -- t8 A Portrait of Khortytsya/Zaporizhzhia under Occupation -- t9 Dutch Mennonites and Yad Vashem Recognition -- t10 Identity and Complicity: The Post−Second World War Emigration of Chortitza Mennonites -- t11 A Usable Past: Soviet Mennonite Memories of the Holocaust -- t12 Selective Memory: Danziger Mennonite Reflections on the Nazi Era, 1945–1950 -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMennonites in the Netherlands, Germany, Poland, and Ukraine lived in communities with Jews and close to various Nazi camps and Holocaust killing sites. As a result of this proximity, Mennonites were neighbours to and witnessed the destruction of European Jews. In some cases they were beneficiaries or even enablers of the Holocaust. Much of this history was forgotten after the war, as Mennonites sought to rebuild or find new homes as refugees. The result was a myth of Mennonite innocence and ignorance that connected their own suffering during the 1930s and 1940s with earlier centuries of persecution and marginalization. European Mennonites and the Holocaust identifies a significant number of Mennonite perpetrators, along with a smaller number of Mennonites who helped Jews survive, examining the context in which they acted. In some cases, theology led them to accept or reject Nazi ideals. In others, Mennonites chose a closer embrace of German identity as a strategy to improve their standing with Germans or for material benefit. A powerful and unflinching examination of a difficult history, European Mennonites and the Holocaust uncovers a more complete picture of Mennonite life in these years, underscoring actions that were not always innocent. Published by the University of Toronto Press in association with the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945) 0aMennoniteszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aMennoniteszEuropexSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCollaborationistszEurope. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xUnderground movementszEurope. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.